"Leadership is a highly valued skill in modern enterprises. It underpins an effective workforce, fosters innovation and creates vibrant, healthy companies. It is also necessary for a robust cyber-security effort. Unfortunately, survey data suggests that senior management is not leading by example when it comes to adopting best cyber-security practices. Getting senior executives to practise what they preach is a crucial step in promoting a healthy culture of enterprise security. The next step is to stop them preaching altogether, and instead to listen. Senior management appears to be unaware of the full importance of data security, yet employees look to these executives for education and leadership on data protection. It is imperative that senior-level executives lead by example and ensure they follow the necessary data security policies to set a precedent among staff. If they fail, they risk creating a culture of non-compliance among employees, and exposing organisations to the risk of a data breach. Nicholas Banks of IronKey explores effective ways to disseminate a culture of cyber-security after best practices are adopted at the top of an organisation."
